{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596426"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:13:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:13:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15408"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15408"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8099"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69794"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8099"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15408"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55249"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19647"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19651"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69794"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInflammatory bowel disease (IBD) encompasses several chronic inflammatory conditions affecting the gastrointestinal tract. The two main types are Crohn disease and ulcerative colitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a characteristic pathological feature of inflammatory bowel disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Disruption of epithelial tight junctions","Inflammation limited to mucosa","Continuous inflammation from rectum to ileum","Normal crypt architecture","Intact intestinal barrier function"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn inflammatory bowel disease, several pathological changes occur. \u003Cstrong\u003EDisruption of epithelial tight junctions\u003C/strong\u003E is a key feature that leads to increased intestinal permeability and barrier dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammation limited to mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as IBD can involve transmural inflammation, particularly in Crohn disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous inflammation from rectum to ileum\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as Crohn disease characteristically shows skip lesions, while ulcerative colitis typically starts in the rectum and extends proximally\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal crypt architecture\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as IBD shows characteristic crypt distortion and crypt abscesses\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntact intestinal barrier function\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as barrier dysfunction is a hallmark of IBD pathophysiology\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese pathological changes contribute to the chronic inflammatory state and symptoms seen in IBD patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Inflammatory bowel disease involves multiple pathological changes including barrier dysfunction, granulomas, crypt abscesses, skip lesions, and transmural inflammation.","Crohn disease and ulcerative colitis have distinct pathological features that aid in diagnosis.","Disruption of intestinal epithelial tight junctions is a key pathological feature that increases intestinal permeability."],"references":["Cai Z, Wang S, Li J. Treatment of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Comprehensive Review. Front Med (Lausanne). 2021 Dec 20;8:765474. doi: 10.3389/fmed.2021.765474. PMID: 34988090; PMCID: PMC8720971","McDowell C, Farooq U, Haseeb M. Inflammatory Bowel Disease. 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29262182","Fakhoury M, Negrulj R, Mooranian A, Al-Salami H. Inflammatory bowel disease: clinical aspects and treatments. J Inflamm Res. 2014 Jun 23;7:113-20. doi: 10.2147/JIR.S65979. PMID: 25075198; PMCID: PMC4106026","Tavakoli P, Vollmer-Conna U, Hadzi-Pavlovic D, Grimm MC. A Review of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Model of Microbial, Immune and Neuropsychological Integration. Public Health Rev. 2021 May 5;42:1603990. doi: 10.3389/phrs.2021.1603990. PMID: 34692176; PMCID: PMC8386758","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55249"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15408"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55249"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T19:46:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T19:47:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8099"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69794"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Su